segments.text: With Christie and capital improvements, the city stopped trying to put them through in about, what, 74, 75?
Oh, I don't know.
That may not be really quite right.
We used to have it very specific.
First, it was a five-year plan.
Then we made a six-year plan.
And then we made it three years specific and three years general.
For capital improvements in the city?
Yeah.
I think the three years specific and the three years general is probably more practical than the five-year plan.
And then we started to just have an intense capital improvement program.
At the same time, we were planning to have a bond issue.
And we were having bond issues every three to five years.
And so really every three years, I guess, over the last decade or so.
So the cattle improvement program was really honed down and got specific around that bond issue.
So this was the next three years and then beyond without any kind of time frame.
So we didn't get involved with all this business about trying to get people's expectations up for the fourth and fifth and sixth years.
when you had no idea what reality might be at that time.
I'll never forget one project called Caroline.
Remember Caroline?
Right, yeah.
Caroline was scheduled for improvements in 1958 on one of these listed capital improvements.
And I had to suffer with that from 1958 until I guess Caroline was finally paid.
And it's all paid now.
I think so.
I mean, I remember part of it being paved in the mid-'60s when I used to go out in that area of town.
Mid-'60s?
Seems like it was mid-'60s.
Well, I was driving by 65 or 66, so.
I've forgotten.
I think Carolina was paved in the 70s, the part that I'm talking about.
I mean, completely paved out.
Yeah, curb and gutter and sidewalk and all.
Yeah.
But 15 years, whatever it was, 20 years later,
And yet, the reason was it shouldn't have been put there in the first place.
Carol Lane, I mean, it shouldn't have been on the capital improvement program in the first place.
Was it too early?
Yeah, in terms of priorities.
In fact, I don't know that it was in their best interest to have it paved when it was paved.
Because Carol Lane was sitting there with its residential nature pretty well preserved.
It didn't have to happen what happened to Earhart.
It was still residential in nature.
Well, who was setting up those priorities for the...
The usual staff.
At that time it was headed by planning and it was backed up by public works and engineering.
But there's no way to set priorities like that and make sense out of them that far ahead of time.
If you think about planning and
We've been fighting here, our sewer planning.
We had a very optimistic plan submitted three years ago before Peso collapsed.
And the city was growing it very rapidly.
But we're having to eat that plan now because this involves the state and the EPA and everybody.
And they want us to prove that our new growth forecasts are correct.
Well, I'll tell you right now, there's nobody in this town who can forecast more than three months ahead of time right now.
We don't know where the city's going next year, next five years.
We don't know the next three months.
Look at the major economic activities that have happened in South Texas over the last 20 years and ask yourself how many of them were forecasted.
Almost no one forecasted what was going to happen to the price of natural gas.
Next to nobody.
Even though everybody had a kind of vague feeling about the peso going down, nobody forecasted even to the year.
Or to the extent.
Or to the extent, right.
Nobody really forecasted the impact of the problems with foreign oil.
You can identify almost every really major impact on South Texas, and it wasn't anybody's plan.
And so that doesn't mean we shouldn't plan, because we need to have the plan set forth.
But we've got to recognize that those places where the plan tends to get stuck and rigid have to be avoided.
And that's what the capital improvement program process was doing.
You get people who had no idea what was going to happen six years from now trying to forecast six years hence.
Well, it's nice to forecast the things you have a fairly good idea about.
You can come pretty close to forecasting such values, I think.
And you can relate that to the consumption of land.
If we grow 2,000 people a year or for six years, that's 12,000 people.
And the average family size is three plus, whatever it is.
And that equates to 4,000 families.
And 4,000 families equates to, we'll say, 700 acres or 600 acres of land.
So it's reasonable.
When we look at the whole city and we say, well, we think this guy's going to be able to put up a 40-acre development here.
This is going to happen over here.
And we've got sewer service here and water service here.
Yeah, we can take care of 700 families this way and that way.
That's good planning, as long as you realize that it needs to stay that flexible, that you obviously covered a whole bunch of assumptions there.

Now for us to start getting specific and saying in the fourth year, we're going to build this road, because there are going to be 200 or more houses out here, all of a sudden it's starting to get awfully fuzzy, because those 200 houses may come first, they may come last.
Now, if we have a good reason why they might come first, that's something else.
Let's say there's a big ministry going down the street from them, and yes, that makes sense that that's going to be the hottest area.
Well, then maybe we can show that as a priority street in the first year.
But it sure gets weak by the fifth year, and the sixth year, and the seventh year.
I think somebody's tried the 10-year program.
That's just wild.
To me, if you can't show how you're going to pay for it, then you probably aren't going to get the quality of decision-making that you need from them.
first-level planner, to the city manager, to the city council, to the planning commission.

I watch so many planning commissions sit down with the capital improvement program and say, well, what's the bond election going to be, and where's the money coming from, and for all the stuff that the money's not set for, they just don't even read it.
And all of a sudden, that becomes the approved program.
Somebody says, when's my street going to be paved?
Oh, well, you're set down in the fifth year, ma'am.
And what level of decision would you do it?
Some low staff person scheduled it.
And everybody else was too busy worrying about these first three years to even look at this fifth year.
And all of a sudden, a whole bunch of false expectations.
People saying, ah, my storm steward's in the fifth year.
That's 1987.
I can count on that.
So you're saying that anything after three years.
Well, after the time that you can pay for it.
Because you don't get the decision making process doesn't work unless you've got to pay for what your dreams are.
All you're doing is listing projects.
We had a project in Corpus Christi that made it into four or five capital improvement programs.
And it was for the birds.
I feel guilty as much as anybody else.
I didn't really think of it and thought through well enough.
But still, I knew it was representing a problem.
Six points.
Why?
You know, six points back in the late 50s was just a traffic nightmare before the Crosstown Expressway opened up.
Terrible, you know.
If you had to go to work through six points, you added 10 minutes time to that thing.

So our people came up with a fancy plan to go around Six Points, bypass around Six Points, and then to parallel 6th and 7th, I think it was, it may have been 5th and, no, it may have been 7th, I think it was 5th, 6th and 7th Street.
By Spahn Hospital?
Yeah.
Right, yeah.
Well, this side of Spahn Hospital, I say this side, you know, between Spahn and Six Points.
Yeah, between Spahn and Six Points.
To parallel those and to come down, and also to cut...

The Del Mar 3rd connection, right through that block there by Spahn Hospital, right through all those houses, so that you can make that transition smoothly without having to go and make a right-hand turn, a left-hand turn.
Dumb recommendation, that one.
That's one of the dumbest.
I didn't know a person in the city that's ever been hurt by having to turn down Del Mar and then make a left-hand turn versus being able to merge in across those fine houses.
I think it only takes about six or seven of those houses out in order to make that a smooth transition.
What does a smooth transition do?
In fact, it makes the traffic a little slower to make them have to make a right-hand turn than a left-hand turn.
But anyway, this was grandiose and crazy.
I mean, it was going to be expensive.
It involved putting some parking lots in Six Points and buying all that property.
And it involved making Alameda become Staples.
And Staples became, let's see.
Anyway, I guess going south, Staples continued to be Staples and Alameda
No, Alameda, that's right.
Alameda became Staples, and Staples became Alameda.
Alameda was over there by the Six Points Theater.
And in essence, it left the Six Points area as Staples.
Alameda came in, and it went north as Staples.
Great project if money was no object, and if somebody had some redevelopment plans to go with it.
But it was a transportation planner's project.
The truth of the matter is, the property owners didn't really agree.
There was no money for the parking lots.
And if you moved all the traffic around it, you'd probably kill six points.
You didn't have that much capacity to come back.
The economic activity around it wasn't sufficient to make that a really desirable location.
So what we would have probably done is simply kill what was there and spend millions of dollars on this cotton picking way around the circle.
A few years later, some relatively simple traffic signal improvements were made, and the drainage problems were corrected, and the streets were paying better.
And I don't think anybody today would recommend that grandiose plan of Six Points.
It economically didn't make any sense.
You're spending so much money for the few stores that were left, and in the process, isolating those stores from their own customers.
And Six Points, actually, one of its biggest customers is its walk-in traffic from the older neighborhood
out toward Delmar.
And by doing this, she made it almost impossible for the person to walk there to get there.
So how was that plan defeated then?
It just died in the planning department?
No, no, no.
Well, I mean, first of all, it just got kicked out of capital improvement programs.
But the point I'm making is for two or three years, it was in there.
People were saying, hey, this is a scheduled project.
Why isn't it on the next bond election?
And it never really was thought through well.
It was

a transportation planner's solution that never had to stand the test of reality of going through the whole process of other departments giving and taking and the planning commission criticism and the honest ending cost estimates as to what it was going to cost.
Because it was in the plan and not in the real program.
And that to me just almost forces the current planning process to be tied to a real program
where the planner and the operator have to make it happen.
Like how much community development money are you going to have in the next three years?
That's real.
What's the opportunity to get federal funds through the highway department?
That's real.
The bond issue?
That's real.
And the Corpus Christi had to have an election for every bond issue.
Now, those are real things.
If you're going to have to raise the money, then you've really put the project through the ringer.
And when it comes out, you're willing to pay for it.
But the rest of it.
You just kind of say, well, we'll show it as bond issues.
We'll show we're going to have $5 million this year, $6 million next, $7 million, $8 million, $9 million, $10 million, $11 million.
We're going to finance it like so.
We're going to sell as many revenue bonds as we need.
So we'll sell a bunch of sewerage bonds to the sewer plants.
Just very rarely do you see a capital improvement program when they really say that in the fifth year, it's going to require a 75% sewer rate increase, or it's going to require taxes or less than so.
They just address the first part of the plan.
Well, I appreciate you going into that, and I thank you very much for your time.
Is that really what you need?

Well, it's given me a lot of good information, and I think about the growth of Corpus Christi, and perhaps it's a... Everyone has their own particular point of view, and if we're going to look at how planning has affected the growth of a city...
We'd like to get the points of view of a group of people who are involved in the growth, not just one person, not just one department at one specific time.
I feel very strongly about protecting the Bayfront.
I do too.
I'm not so sure it's being protected right now.
That's one reason I'm down here and not over there.
development of the bayfront and the beach, for that matter.
The beach is going to be one of the long, low condominiums.
Block to block, you're not going to be able to hit that peak.
If you're not in the first half of the block, you're not even going to be able to see it before approaching the beach.
You'll probably notice the star of the condominiums.
And they're so eager to get commercial uses on the bayfront that it's just killing them.
Who is that?
Well, it was the last council.
which literally is the reason I'm not there.
Is it a mixture of council, Chamber of Commerce?
Oh, not so much Chamber of Commerce.
Maybe it's been council, which has been controlled by developers, and they've just been so gung-ho to make things happen on that paper.
Mayor Pro Tem said to me one day over a cocktail that if I push the paper on development projects, that she'd be with me 100%, and if I wouldn't, she was going to get me.
That's how important it was to her.
And I never really have understood exactly why.
Of course, most of that council was in the development business.
There were people who either their hobby or who had direct livelihood was construction, condominiums, semi-condominiums, that kind of thing.
I'm not saying that the projects are all bad.
There have been some nice projects.
But that cocktail bar marina office, have you been along the background recently?
Uh, well, yeah.
Yeah, I have.
Well, you may not have noticed it yet, but on the middle teahead, where the Marine Office used to be, Lawrence Street Teahead?
Right.

The Marine Office was taken out with Hurricane Allen, and they, with a private-public participation cooperation project, they put back a new Marine Office, but it's got a big cocktail-inch grill on top of it.
And it just stands up like an elephant out there in the water.
But I hope they don't do too much of that.
But they've been pushing this bill.
And I don't know whether you keep up with the discussion or not.
Yeah, I do.
All of a sudden, a couple weeks ago, there was this amazing discovery that there was going to be a problem with B zones.
I don't know if you're familiar with B zones or not.
But in the floodplain area.
Right.
Is that something to do with insurance?
Yeah, a federal insurance program.
But if the city agrees to clean it, they've got to comply with all the rules.
And you can't build below the floodplain.
Well, on the Gulf side, there's what's called a velocity zone on top of it, a V-zone.
And they're saying now that this is brand new information to them.
Well, a V-zone presentation was made as a factor after Hurricane Alan.
And that was 1980, OK.
All of a sudden, there's news, news about the V-Zone.
How that's going to cause the landfill problem.
I just laughed up my sleeve.
Everybody knew.
It was in the papers, even.

The fact that, see, that's one of the reasons why it took so long to repair some of the stuff after Hurricane Allen, was the feds were saying that the improvements are going to have to be consistent with the V-Zone calculations.
Well, the hotels are happening.
I guess I didn't mention that.
That was always a major concern, is that we have hotels that support the convention center.
And I felt very confident that it happened as soon as the interest rates dropped.
Remember, when the convention center was finished, the interest rates were way up in the 16th, 17th, 18th percent period.
And it was obvious to most of us that when the interest rates dropped, that part would take care of itself and get Marriott and Treasury Harbor House and the...
That's why it's been on the beach and two of the others have built this in the last couple of years.
It certainly has changed the look of downtown Corpus Christi quite a bit.
Well, thank you.
I really appreciate your time.
You're welcome.
Good luck to you.
